<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">February to May.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="9" type="conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">
Least Concern (
<bibRefCitation author="Raimondo, D" journalOrPublisher="South African National Biodiversity Institute, Pretoria," pageId="0" pageNumber="9" pagination="23 - 35" refId="B24" refString="Raimondo, D, von Staden, L, Foden, W, Victor, JE, Helme, NA, Turner, RC, Kamundi, DA, Manyama, PA, 2009. Red List of South African Plants. Strelitzia 25. South African National Biodiversity Institute, Pretoria, 86: 23 - 35" title="Red List of South African Plants. Strelitzia 25." volume="86" year="2009">Raimondo et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="9" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Diagnostic characters.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hilliard &amp; B. L. Burtt, Notes Roy. Bot. Gard. Edinburgh 43 (3): 343" authorityYear="1986" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cynoglossum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cynoglossum alticola" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alticola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Cynoglossum alticola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by its thick, convex nutlets. Among the southern African species, it has a unique appearance due to the presence of woolly trichomes that cover the whole plant. Furthermore, it has larger nutlets (6-9
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-6 mm) than other species (less than 6
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5 mm). According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Hilliard, OM" journalOrPublisher="Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" pagination="345 - 405" publicationUrl="https://agris.fao.org/agris-search/search.do?recordID=GB19790370487" refId="B14" refString="Hilliard, OM, Burtt, BL, 1986. Notes on some plants of southern Africa chiefly from Natal: XLIII. Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh 43 (3): 345 - 405, https://agris.fao.org/agris-search/search.do?recordID=GB19790370487" title="Notes on some plants of southern Africa chiefly from Natal: XLIII." url="https://agris.fao.org/agris-search/search.do?recordID=GB19790370487" volume="43" year="1986">Hilliard and Burtt (1986)</bibRefCitation>
, this species is related to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. alpinum" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alpinum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">C. alpinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Brand) B.L. Burtt from the highlands of Ethiopia, with which it shares nutlet shape and size, as well as the leaf texture and colour. The difference is observed on the fornices (small crests in the corolla tube of a plant), as in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. alticola" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alticola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">C. alticola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are broad and short while in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. alpinum" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alpinum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">C. alpinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are long and narrow.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="9" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">
The species is restricted to the Eastern Cape Province in South Africa and Lesotho (Figure 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Distribution of Cynoglossum alticola based on the specimens examined." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.193.72270.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/658888" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">4</figureCitation>
), where it is found growing on mountainous terrain and on damp slopes near streams.
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/phytokeys.193.72270.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/658888" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" start="Figure 4" startId="F4">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Figure 4.</emphasis>
Distribution of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hilliard &amp; B. L. Burtt, Notes Roy. Bot. Gard. Edinburgh 43 (3): 343" authorityYear="1986" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cynoglossum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cynoglossum alticola" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alticola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="9">Cynoglossum alticola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on the specimens examined.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
